replies.msg: Kai果pad同我打學界用嘅差唔多

In his press conference yesterday, Thomas Tuchel stated that Christian Pulisic’s time to start a league game under him could come at any moment and today at Leeds, he proves the American is very much in his plans by naming him in the starting line-up.

Pulisic will play in attack alongside Hakim Ziyech and with Kai Havertz in a central role. Ahead of kick-off the boss has also spoken about the young German, but he begins with his selection of Pulisic.

‘It is the moment to step up for him,’ he said.

‘He has waited now for a long time and he is super-hungry to play. He has had a big impact for us from the bench so it is the moment now to start and show what he can do for us from the beginning. He is very attacking and very intense and we want to play in the opponents’ half and control the rhythm.’

Tuchel praised Havertz’s performance on Monday against Everton after many games out and added:

‘When he was able to come back we had very intense matches in the Champions League and against Man United and Liverpool and it was not the moment to throw him in there, because he had to adapt and he was lacking load so we put extra load in training.

‘I was doubting a little bit the decision to let him start against Everton but we did and I was happy because he proved he has the physical capacity to step up to a performance like this. He was impressive and decisive which is why we decided to give him another game from the start to keep the momentum going.’

原本今場出高囝

The head coach confirmed Mason Mount and N’Golo Kante come into the side today as they are suspended for the midweek Champions League match.

‘Normally I don’t like to do this but in central midfield we miss Jorgi and Mason on Wednesday so we took the decision to give Kova a rest and don’t take the risk, because normally this is his game to start also. But we have two suspensions so we went for this decision.

‘It is almost the same line-up as against Liverpool and we had some changes against Everton to give us some fresh legs and fresh heads. We expect a different style from Leeds than against Everton and we want to have some advantages for that.

‘If there is an intensive game coming we feel absolutely able to cope with it because we have the physical capability and the speed and it is also intense to play against us, so we are ready to go.’
